In this repo, "the assistant axis" is a single direction (a unit vector) in the residual-stream activation space of Qwen3-32B at a target layer, published as `lu-christina/assistant-axis-vectors`. "Above" / "below" refers to the **sign of the per-token scalar projection** onto that direction — i.e. it's a 1D number, not a region in space.

### How the number is computed

For every generated token, `leash.py` hooks the target layer and does a dot product of the last-position residual stream with the axis unit vector:

```150:153:leash.py
def _monitor_hook(self, module, inputs, outputs):
    hidden = outputs[0] if isinstance(outputs, tuple) else outputs
    last = hidden[:, -1, :]
    self._last_projection = float((last @ self.axis_unit).item())
```

Each `{token, token_id, projection, capped}` SSE event carries that scalar. So "projection" is a signed real number per token.

### What above / below means

- **Above (projection > 0)** — the residual state at that token has a positive dot product with the assistant-axis direction. In the project's framing this is the "assistant-aligned" side of the axis. The dashboard explicitly labels a token's positive peak as "Peak assistant alignment":

```162:170:dashboard/src/lib/traceAnalysis.ts
  if (peak && peak.tok.projection > 0) {
    events.push({
      kind: "peak",
      tokenIndex: peak.tok.i ?? peak.i,
      token: peak.tok.token,
      projection: peak.tok.projection,
      label: `Peak assistant alignment (+${peak.tok.projection.toFixed(1)})`,
    });
  }
```

- **Below (projection < 0)** — the residual is pointing *against* the assistant direction. The project calls this "drift off the assistant axis", with severity bands defined in `traceAnalysis.ts`:

```3:6:dashboard/src/lib/traceAnalysis.ts
/** Projection below this is considered a major drift off the assistant axis. */
export const DEEP_DRIFT_THRESHOLD = -30;
/** Single-token drop larger than this is flagged as a sharp deviation. */
export const SHARP_DROP_THRESHOLD = 12;
```

```193:199:dashboard/src/lib/traceAnalysis.ts
  if (stats.mean >= -5) {
    parts.push("Stays close to the assistant axis on average.");
  } else if (stats.mean >= -18) {
    parts.push("Mild drift — mean projection below neutral but not extreme.");
  } else {
    parts.push("Sustained drift off the assistant axis across this turn.");
  }
```

### Calibration in practice

The axis isn't zero-centered for ordinary generation on this task — Qwen3-32B sits negative most of the time. From the sweep table in `README.md`, mean per-token projection across whole sessions lands around **−14 to −22**, with positive peaks (~+17) only really showing up in `think_on` cells. So:

| projection range | dashboard reading |
|---|---|
| `> 0` | "above the axis" — tokens actively aligned with assistant-persona direction (rare, mostly inside `<think>`) |
| `−5 … 0` | close to baseline assistant tone |
| `−5 … −18` | mild drift |
| `< −18` (and especially `≤ −30`) | major / deep drift |

The optional **clamp** (`--clamp` / `clamp_on`) is the published capping intervention from `safety-research/assistant-axis`: it limits how *high* the projection can go on the assistant-aligned side by editing the residual stream — i.e. it pulls "above the axis" tokens back down, leaving "below" untouched.

### What it doesn't mean

One of the headline conclusions of the experiment is in [README lines 243-249](README.md#L243): the sign / magnitude of this projection is best read as a **decision-making / persona detector**, not a reward-hacking detector. Hack tokens average ~−10.85, fix tokens ~−9.81, plain `<think>` filler ~−13.98 — so "less below" correlates with the model doing structured code reasoning at all, regardless of whether it's about to hack or fix.

 I'm pulling together the key technical details: the assistant axis is a unit vector from the residual stream activation space that gets loaded into the system, and the projection works by computing a dot product between the hidden state and that unit vector to produce a signed scalar value per token, with "above" and "below" the axis representing different directions in that activation space.

